{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"5191","authors":[{"fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre","id":"6"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:36 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:36 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">As in other Asian languages such as Japanese and Korean, Tibetan has developed an honorific register that make it possible to express social relations through linguistic usage. The honorific should be understood as a sophisticated form of politeness expressed through personal pronouns, names, verbs, auxiliaries, and even adjectives and adverbs. The honorific register, called <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5e\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span>, is used for people of superior and equal social standing, and even between friends and married couples. The ordinary register, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f90\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f40\u0fb1\u0f74\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f0b<\/span>, is used for all others, that is, those younger than oneself (although the honorific is sometimes used with certain juniors) and social inferiors.<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">Students of Tibetan should certainly learn both registers, but if you were to learn only one, the ordinary register would be better for two reasons: some people without much education hardly use the honorific register; and secondly, even if you use honorifics to another person you should always use ordinary terms (in the absence of humilifics) for yourself. And finally the good news: quite a number of words have only one form.<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">Most nouns, adjectives, and adverbs have only one type of honorific.<\/p><table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"> <tbody> <tr> <td width=\"113\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><strong>Noun<\/strong><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"113\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><strong>Ordinary<\/strong><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"113\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><strong>Honorific<\/strong><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"113\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Tea<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"113\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f47\u0f0b<\/span><em><\/em><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"113\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f66\u0f7c\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f47\u0f0b<\/span><em><\/em><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"113\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Water<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"113\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f46\u0f74\u0f0b<em><\/em><\/span><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"113\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f46\u0f56\u0f0b<\/span><em><\/em><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"113\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Book<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"113\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f56\u0f0b<em><\/em><\/span><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"113\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f55\u0fb1\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f56\u0f0b<\/span><em><\/em><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <\/tbody> <\/table><p class=\"Paragraph\">For verbs, however, as well as for pronouns, there are several types of honorific:<\/p><p>1. <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0fa4\u0fb1\u0f72\u0f62\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f4f\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f5e\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> The \u201cgeneral honorific\u201d (H)<\/p><p>2. <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5e\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f50\u0f7c\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b<\/span> The \u201chigh honorific\u201d (HH)<\/p><p>3. <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f58\u0f60\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f5f\u0f74\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f60\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f5e\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> The \u201chumilific\u201d (h)<\/p><p>4. <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f55\u0fb1\u0f7c\u0f42\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f49\u0f72\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f40\u0fb1\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f5e\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> The \u201cdouble honorific\u201d (hH)<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">The general and high honorifics correspond to forms of politeness that indicate a respectful attitude toward the <em>subject of an action. <\/em>The high honorific conveys an even more polite and reverential attitude than the general honorific, and is used especially in the case of high lamas and State dignitaries. The humilific<a href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]<\/a> is systematically used for the first person as the subject, but more generally to indicate a respectful attitude on the part of the speaker toward the person to whom that action is directed (which, from a syntactic perspective, may comprise various complements: object, indirect object, etc.). It should be emphasized that the honorific is <em>never used with reference to oneself, <\/em>and for the first person the humilific is consequently needed.<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">Finally, the double honorific denotes that both the subject of the action and the person to whom it is directed are considered by the speaker to merit equal respect. Note that there are only a few high and double honorifics, and they are not often used.<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">Here is an illustration of the different levels:<\/p><table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"> <tbody> <tr> <td width=\"102\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><strong>Verb<\/strong><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"174\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><strong>Humilific (h)<\/strong><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"147\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><strong>Ordinary<\/strong><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"174\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><strong>Honorific (H)<\/strong><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"102\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">To drink<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"174\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5e\u0f74\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"147\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f50\u0f74\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"174\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f58\u0f46\u0f7c\u0f51\u0f0b<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"102\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">To give<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"174\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f55\u0f74\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> <em><\/em><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"147\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0fa4\u0fb2\u0f51\u0f0b<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"174\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"102\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">To stay, sit<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"174\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">\u2014<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"147\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f66\u0fa1\u0f51\u0f0b<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"174\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f5e\u0f74\u0f42\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"102\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">To go<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"174\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f45\u0f62\u0f0b<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"147\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f42\u0fb2\u0f7c\u0f0b<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"174\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f55\u0f7a\u0f56\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"102\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">To speak<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"174\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f40\u0f60\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f7c\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f5e\u0f74\u0f66\u0f0b<em><\/em><\/span><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"147\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f90\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f46\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f64\u0f51\u0f0b<\/span><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"174\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f40\u0f60\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f7c\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b<em><\/em><\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <\/tbody> <\/table><p class=\"Paragraph\">\u00a0Special cases of high and double honorifics:<\/p><table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"> <tbody> <tr> <td width=\"113\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><strong>Verb<\/strong><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"238\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><strong>High Honorific (HH)<\/strong><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"238\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><strong>Double Honorific (hH)<\/strong><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"113\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">To give<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"238\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">\u2014<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"238\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f55\u0f74\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span><em><\/em><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"113\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">To stay, sit<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"238\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f5e\u0f74\u0f42\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f51\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f47\u0f42\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span><em><\/em><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"238\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">\u2014<\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"113\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">To go<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"238\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f46\u0f72\u0f56\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f92\u0fb1\u0f74\u0f62\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span><em><\/em><\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"238\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">\u2014<\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <tr> <td width=\"113\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">To speak<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"238\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\">\u2014<\/p> <\/td> <td width=\"238\" valign=\"top\"> <p class=\"Paragraph\"><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f40\u0f60\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f7c\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f5e\u0f74\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b<em><\/em><\/span><\/p> <\/td> <\/tr> <\/tbody> <\/table><p class=\"Paragraph\">Perfect mastery of honorifics is not easy,<a href=\"#_ftn2\">[2]<\/a> but you need not worry too much about this because Tibetans themselves often make mistakes! A common expression, \u201clame honorifics\u201d (<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5e\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f90\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f46\u0f42\u0f0b<\/span>), is used to signify a sentence in which the speaker puts some elements in the honorific but mistakenly leaves others on the ordinary level. The misuse of honorifics is a common source of amusement for Tibetans.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">The basis for a mastery of the honorific language is a sound knowledge of the pronouns and a few of the main nouns, verbs (especially the main verbs of movement, speech and action), and auxiliaries. The <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5e\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> vocabulary will gradually increase with usage.<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">The honorific language is especially used in Standard Tibetan and the dialects of Central Tibet and Tsang, as well as certain outlying regions such as Mustang, in Nepal. It is also very important in Tibetan literature, where it may even play a grammatical role since it can substitute for the subject and other markers of person by establishing the relationship between characters, and hence identify them. Contrary to a widespread belief, the honorific is not altogether absent in the dialects of Kham and Amdo, even though it is much less frequently used than in Central Tibet.<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">Most honorifics are derivatives of ordinary terms, and relatively few are original. For the most part, nouns are formed by the use of honorific prefixes. There are perhaps just a dozen or so such prefixes, corresponding to honorific terms for body parts: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f90\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cbody,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f55\u0fb1\u0f42\u0f0b<\/span> \u201chand,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f56\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span> \u201chead,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0fa4\u0fb1\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> \u201ceyes,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5e\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cmouth,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5e\u0f56\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cleg,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f97\u0f42\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> \u201ctongue,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f50\u0f74\u0f42\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cmind,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f40\u0f60\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cspeech,\u201d as well as a few prefixes derived from verbs: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f66\u0f7c\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cto pray,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f5e\u0f7a\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cto take,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f5f\u0f72\u0f58\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cto sleep,\u201d etc.<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">Each prefix is associated with a very wide semantic field related to its original meaning. Thus the prefix <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f90\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span> often appears in words denoting not only body parts but also physical activities, bodily representations, kinship ties, clothing, belongings, social ranks, certain illnesses, and so on. For example: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f90\u0f74\u0f0b\u0f41\u0fb2\u0f42\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cblood,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f90\u0f74\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f9f\u0f7c\u0f51\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cshirt,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f90\u0f74\u0f0b\u0f46\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cpossessions,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f90\u0f74\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f62\u0f99\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cstatue,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f90\u0f74\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f42\u0fb2\u0f7c\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cguest,\u201d etc.<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">Verbs fall into two categories:<\/p><p>1. Verbs consisting of a noun and a verbalizer (these constitute the majority)<\/p><p>2. Simple verbs<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">In the first case, the honorific is obtained by putting the noun that precedes the verb in the honorific (according to the principle outlined above) and then replacing the verbalizer by its honorific (or humilific) homologue. Here are some verbs with common honorific verbalizers:<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> honorific for <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0fb1\u0f7a\u0f51\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cto do\u201d (<em>verbalizer<\/em>) and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0fa4\u0fb2\u0f51\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cto give\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f66\u0f90\u0fb1\u0f7c\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> honorific for <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f62\u0f92\u0fb1\u0f56\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cto do,\u201d \u201cto make\u201d (<em>verbalizer<\/em>)<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f4f\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> honorific for <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f4f\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cto send\u201d (<em>verbalizer<\/em>)<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f5e\u0f7a\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> honorific for <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f7a\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cto take,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5f\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cto eat,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f50\u0f74\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cto drink\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5e\u0f74\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> humilific for <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5f\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cto eat,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f50\u0f74\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cto drink,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f7a\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cto take,\u201d <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f64\u0f51\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cto say\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f55\u0f74\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> humilific for <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0fa4\u0fb2\u0f51\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cto give\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f5e\u0f7a\u0f44\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> honorific for <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f44\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cto rise\u201d (<em>verbalizer<\/em>)<\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">\u00a0Following are some examples of verbs with these honorific verbalizers:<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f40\u0f0b\u0f56\u0fb1\u0f7a\u0f51\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo work\u201d > <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f55\u0fb1\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> (H)<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f47\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f50\u0f74\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo drink tea\u201d > <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f66\u0f7c\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f47\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f46\u0f7c\u0f51\u0f0b<\/span> (H) or <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f66\u0f7c\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f47\u0f0b\u0f5e\u0f74\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> (h)<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f58\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f4f\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo set fire\u201d > <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5e\u0f74\u0f42\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f4f\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> (H)<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f54\u0f62\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f92\u0fb1\u0f56\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo photograph\u201d > <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f90\u0f74\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f54\u0f62\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f66\u0f90\u0fb1\u0f7c\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> (H)<\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">In the case of certain simple verbs, the honorific entails a different lexical root.<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f42\u0fb2\u0f7c\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo go\u201d > <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f55\u0f7a\u0f56\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> (H)<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f58\u0f50\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo see\u201d > <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f5f\u0f72\u0f42\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> (H)<\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">Note that there are only a few adjectives and adverbs that have a true honorific form. In such cases, the honorific has a different root from the ordinary term.<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f90\u0fb1\u0f72\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cHappy,\u201d \u201cpleasant,\u201d and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5e\u0f72\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cDelicious\u201d > <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0fa4\u0fb2\u0f7c\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b<\/span> (H)<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f58\u0f49\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTogether\u201d > <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0fb7\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f92\u0fb1\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> (H)<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f58\u0f42\u0fb1\u0f7c\u0f42\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cFast,\u201d \u201cquickly\u201d > <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0fa9\u0f7c\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b<\/span> (H, rare)<\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">In a few rare cases, the honorific form of the adjective is formed by using a suffix <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b<\/span> pronounced <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f7c\u0f0b<\/span>:<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f56\u0f7c\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cSoft\u201d > <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f56\u0f7c\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f7c\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f58\u0f42\u0f7c\u0f0b\u0f5a\u0f7c\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cCapable\u201d > <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f56\u0f74\u0f0b\u0f5a\u0f7c\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f7c\u0f0b<\/span> <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f56\u0f7a\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cQuiet,\u201d \u201ccalm\u201d > <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f56\u0f7a\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f7c\u0f0b<\/span> <\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">Finally, it should be emphasized that respect is shown not only by using terminology but through a wide repertoire of appropriate gestures. Even nowadays, in many rural areas, people greet visitors by protruding their tongues, joining their hands and bowing slightly. The guest of honor always goes first and takes the highest seat, usually located in the innermost part of the room. He always receives the choicest food, served with deferential gestures in a quiet voice, and so on.<\/p><hr size=\"1\" \/><p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\">[1]<\/a> This term was coined by Beyer; see <em>The Classical Tibetan Language<\/em> (Albany: State University of New York Press, 1992).<\/p><p><a href=\"#_ftnref2\">[2]<\/a> The use of honori\ufb01c registers may entail true linguistic virtuosity, to the extent that not only pronouns, but also adjectives, adverbs, verbs, and auxiliaries should be in honori\ufb01c form, while the speaker should also diminish himself or herself by using the appropriate humili\ufb01cs.<\/p>","title":""}]}
